Ecoregion: Sierra Nevada Mixed Conifer Forest
EPA Ecoregion: Sierra Nevada (6)
Elevation range: 1000-2500 meters
Precipitation: 800-1500 mm annually
Climate: Mediterranean-influenced montane
Dominant species: Ponderosa Pine (Pinus ponderosa), White Fir (Abies concolor), Jeffrey Pine (Pinus jeffreyi), Incense-cedar (Calocedrus decurrens), Sugar Pine (Pinus lambertiana)
Fire regime: mixed_severity, interval [10, 25] years
Recovery: Ground cover in [1, 2] years, canopy closure in [25, 50] years
Carbon sequestration rate: 4.5 tonnes CO2/ha/year
Fires in this region: dixie_2021, caldor_2021, creek_2020, camp_2018, rim_2013

Ecoregion: Sierra Nevada Lower Montane Forest
EPA Ecoregion: Sierra Nevada (6)
Elevation range: 500-1200 meters
Precipitation: 500-1000 mm annually
Climate: Mediterranean
Dominant species: Ponderosa Pine (Pinus ponderosa), Black Oak (Quercus kelloggii), Canyon Live Oak (Quercus chrysolepis), Interior Live Oak (Quercus wislizeni), Gray Pine (Pinus sabiniana)
Fire regime: low_to_mixed_severity, interval [5, 20] years
Recovery: Ground cover in [1, 1] years, canopy closure in [20, 40] years
Carbon sequestration rate: 3.5 tonnes CO2/ha/year

Recovery: Ground cover in [1, 2] years, canopy closure in [30, 60] years

Climate: Mediterranean

Fire regime: stand_replacing, interval [30, 100] years
Recovery: Ground cover in [1, 2] years, canopy closure in [0, 0] years
Carbon sequestration rate: 2.0 tonnes CO2/ha/year
Fires in this region: thomas_2017, woolsey_2018

Ecoregion: Central Western Sierra Foothills
EPA Ecoregion: Sierra Nevada Foothills (7)

Precipitation: 350-800 mm annually
Climate: Hot Mediterranean
Dominant species: Blue Oak (Quercus douglasii), Interior Live Oak (Quercus wislizeni), Gray Pine (Pinus sabiniana), California Buckeye (Aesculus californica)
Fire regime: low_to_moderate_severity, interval [10, 30] years
Recovery: Ground cover in [1, 1] years, canopy closure in [15, 30] years

RISK THRESHOLD: Burn Severity
 - threshold_negligible: 0.1
 - threshold_minor: 0.25
 - threshold_moderate: 0.5
 - threshold_significant: 0.7
 - threshold_critical: 0.85
 - language_mapping: [Complex Rule]

RISK THRESHOLD: Erosion Risk
 - slope_degrees_low: 10
 - slope_degrees_moderate: 20
 - slope_degrees_high: 30
 - combined_factors: slope > 15° AND burn_severity > 0.5 → mention erosion, slope < 10° → do not mention erosion regardless of severity, slope > 30° AND any burn → always mention erosion

RISK THRESHOLD: Vegetation Loss
 - threshold_negligible: 0.15
 - threshold_minor: 0.3
 - threshold_moderate: 0.5
 - interpretation: [Complex Rule]

RISK THRESHOLD: Water Quality Impact
 - triggers: Burn perimeter includes stream/river → assess sediment risk, Burn perimeter includes lake/reservoir → assess water quality, No water bodies in perimeter → do not mention water quality

RISK MENTION RULE: Erosion Risk
MENTION IF:
 - slope_degrees > 15 AND burn_severity > 0.40
 - slope_degrees > 25 AND any_burn_detected
 - debris_flow_zone_nearby
DO NOT MENTION IF:
 - slope_degrees < 10
 - burn_severity < 0.20
 - flat terrain regardless of severity

RISK MENTION RULE: Habitat Impact
MENTION IF:
 - protected_species_habitat_flagged
 - critical_habitat_designation
 - high_biodiversity_zone
DO NOT MENTION IF:
 - common_species_only
 - heavily_modified_landscape
 - no_biodiversity_data_available

RISK MENTION RULE: Water Quality
MENTION IF:
 - water_body_in_burn_perimeter
 - reservoir_or_drinking_water_source_nearby
 - riparian_zone_burned
DO NOT MENTION IF:
 - no_water_bodies_detected
 - water_body_more_than_2km_downstream

RISK MENTION RULE: Structural Damage
MENTION IF:
 - structures_detected_in_burn_area
 - urban_interface_zone
DO NOT MENTION IF:
 - no_structures_detected
 - remote_wildland_area

RISK MENTION RULE: Air Quality
MENTION IF:
 - active_fire OR recent_fire_smoke
 - population_center_downwind
DO NOT MENTION IF:
 - fire_fully_contained
 - remote_area_no_population

FIRE REGIME: Surface Fire Regime
Description: Low-intensity fires that burn along forest floor
Typical ecosystems: temperate_conifer_forest, savanna, open_woodland
Fire return interval: 5-35 years
Typical burn severity: low_to_moderate
Recovery timeline: 1-5 years
Ecological role: Maintains open structure, cycles nutrients, reduces fuel

FIRE REGIME: Crown Fire Regime
Description: High-intensity fires that reach tree canopy
Typical ecosystems: boreal_forest, lodgepole_pine, dense_conifer
Fire return interval: 100-300 years
Typical burn severity: high
Recovery timeline: 20-100 years
Ecological role: Stand replacement, mosaic creation, successional reset

FIRE REGIME: Shrubland Fire Regime
Description: Intense fires in shrub-dominated ecosystems
Typical ecosystems: mediterranean_shrubland, chaparral, fynbos, matorral
Fire return interval: 30-100 years
Typical burn severity: high
Recovery timeline: 5-15 years
Ecological role: Triggers seed germination, maintains shrub dominance

FIRE REGIME: Grassland Fire Regime
Description: Frequent, fast-moving fires in grass-dominated systems
Typical ecosystems: savanna, prairie, steppe, grassland
Fire return interval: 1-10 years
Typical burn severity: low
Recovery timeline: 0.5-2 years
Ecological role: Prevents woody encroachment, nutrient cycling

FIRE REGIME: Peatland Fire Regime
Description: Smoldering fires in organic soils
Typical ecosystems: tropical_peatland, boreal_peatland, wetland
Fire return interval: 500-2000 years
Typical burn severity: extreme_when_dry
Recovery timeline: 100-1000 years
Ecological role: NONE - peatland fires are disturbance outside natural regime

POST-FIRE PHASE: Immediate Phase 0 To 1 Year
Physical Changes:
 - Hydrophobic soil layer formation (high severity)
 - Increased runoff and erosion risk
 - Ash nutrient pulse (short-term)
 - Soil heating kills mycorrhizal fungi to 5-10cm depth
Biological Responses:
 - Herbaceous pioneer species establish first
 - Resprouting species begin basal regeneration
 - Seed bank activation (fire-stimulated germinants)
 - Wildlife may temporarily flee but return quickly
Professional Assessment Focus:
 - Erosion risk on slopes >15°
 - Seed source availability within 200-500m
 - Resprouting vigor of remnant vegetation
 - Invasive species colonization risk

POST-FIRE PHASE: Early Recovery 1 To 5 Years
Physical Changes:
 - Soil stability improves with vegetation cover
 - Hydrophobic layer breaks down
 - Nutrient availability stabilizes
Biological Responses:
 - Shrub canopy closure in shrubland systems
 - Grass dominance in open systems
 - Pioneer trees establish if seed source present
 - Wildlife populations recover
Professional Assessment Focus:
 - Natural regeneration success (seedling counts)
 - Type conversion risk (forest → shrubland)
 - Invasive species dominance
 - Need for active intervention

POST-FIRE PHASE: Mid Recovery 5 To 20 Years
Physical Changes:
 - Soil organic matter rebuilding
 - Hydrological regime stabilizing
Biological Responses:
 - Canopy development in forest systems
 - Successional trajectory becomes clear
 - Late-successional species begin establishing
Professional Assessment Focus:
 - Trajectory toward pre-fire composition
 - Structural complexity development
 - Long-term type conversion
POST-FIRE PHASE: Long Term Recovery 20 Plus Years

VEGETATION RESPONSE: Resprouters
Definition: Survive fire and regrow from protected buds
Mechanisms: basal_burls, lignotubers, root_crown, epicormic_buds
Fire survival: high
Restoration implication: Often do NOT need replanting - check for resprouts first

VEGETATION RESPONSE: Obligate Seeders
Definition: Adults killed by fire, regenerate from seed
Mechanisms: soil_seed_bank, serotinous_cones, canopy_seed_bank
Fire survival: adults die, seeds survive
Restoration implication: May need seeding if seed bank depleted or no seed source

VEGETATION RESPONSE: Fire Stimulated Germinants
Definition: Seeds require fire cues (heat, smoke) to germinate
Mechanisms: heat_scarification, smoke_chemicals, charred_wood_signals
Fire survival: seeds enhanced by fire
Restoration implication: Natural regeneration often excellent - wait before planting

VEGETATION RESPONSE: Fire Sensitive
Definition: Killed by fire, no fire-adaptive traits
Mechanisms: thin_bark, no_seed_bank, no_sprouting
Fire survival: low
Restoration implication: May require active planting if seed source distant

BIOME FIRE ECOLOGY: Mediterranean Ecosystems
Regions: California, Mediterranean Basin, Chile, South Africa (fynbos), SW Australia
Fire regime: shrubland_fire_regime
Typical severity: high
Recovery notes: Fire-adapted, natural regeneration usually excellent
Professional caution: Post-fire invasive grass invasion is major concern
Key adaptations: fire_stimulated_germination, lignotubers, serotiny

BIOME FIRE ECOLOGY: Temperate Conifer Forest
Regions: Western North America, Siberia, Northern Europe, New Zealand
Fire regime: surface_fire_regime to crown_fire_regime (varies)
Typical severity: variable - historically low, increasing
Recovery notes: Depends on severity; high severity may need intervention
Professional caution: Long regeneration times for conifers (decades)
Key adaptations: thick_bark, self_pruning, serotiny_in_some

BIOME FIRE ECOLOGY: Boreal Forest
Regions: Canada, Alaska, Russia, Scandinavia
Fire regime: crown_fire_regime
Typical severity: high
Recovery notes: Stand replacement is natural; mosaic pattern important
Professional caution: Climate change increasing fire frequency beyond adaptation
Key adaptations: serotinous_cones, stand_replacement_adapted

BIOME FIRE ECOLOGY: Tropical Savanna
Regions: Africa, Australia, South America (cerrado), India
Fire regime: grassland_fire_regime
Typical severity: low to moderate
Recovery notes: Very fast grass recovery, tree recovery slower
Professional caution: Fire is necessary - suppression causes woody encroachment
Key adaptations: thick_bark_trees, below_ground_grass_meristems

BIOME FIRE ECOLOGY: Eucalyptus Forest
Regions: Australia, naturalized in California, Portugal, Chile
Fire regime: crown_fire_regime
Typical severity: extreme (highest intensity fires globally)
Recovery notes: Eucalypts resprout vigorously; understory varies
Professional caution: Extremely high fuel loads and fire intensity
Key adaptations: epicormic_sprouting, lignotubers, serotiny_in_some

BIOME FIRE ECOLOGY: Tropical Rainforest
Regions: Amazon, Congo, Southeast Asia, Papua New Guinea
Fire regime: NO_NATURAL_FIRE_REGIME
Typical severity: any fire is damaging
Recovery notes: Very slow recovery; may not recover to rainforest
Professional caution: Fire indicates ecosystem degradation, not natural process
Key adaptations: NONE - not fire adapted

Species: Ponderosa Pine
Scientific name: Pinus ponderosa
Family: Pinaceae
Life form: evergreen_tree
Native range: Sierra Nevada, Klamath Mountains, Cascade Range, Coast Ranges
Elevation: 300-2700 meters
Drought tolerance: high
Fire adaptation: thick_bark
Post-fire response: seed_regeneration
Priority for planting: 1
Planting density: [400, 600] stems/hectare
Survival rate: 70%
Nursery availability: high
Notes: Keystone species in Sierra Nevada mixed conifer forests. Thick bark allows survival of low-intensity surface fires. Creates important wildlife habitat. Historically maintained by frequent low-intensity fire.

Species: White Fir
Scientific name: Abies concolor
Family: Pinaceae
Life form: evergreen_tree
Native range: Sierra Nevada, Klamath Mountains, Southern California mountains
Elevation: 1200-2800 meters
Drought tolerance: moderate
Fire adaptation: thin_bark
Post-fire response: seed_regeneration
Priority for planting: 2
Planting density: [200, 400] stems/hectare
Survival rate: 60%
Nursery availability: moderate
Notes: Shade-tolerant species that fills in forest understory. Important for late-successional habitat. Consider reduced planting density to maintain historical open forest structure.

Species: Black Oak
Scientific name: Quercus kelloggii
Family: Fagaceae
Life form: deciduous_tree
Native range: Sierra Nevada, Klamath Mountains, Coast Ranges
Elevation: 200-2400 meters
Drought tolerance: high
Fire adaptation: vigorous_resprouter
Post-fire response: basal_sprouting
Priority for planting: 1
Planting density: [100, 200] stems/hectare
Survival rate: 65%
Nursery availability: moderate
Notes: Critical mast species for wildlife. Vigorous resprouter - often does not need replanting if root system survives. Check for resprouts before planting. Cultural significance to California Native American tribes.

Species: Incense-cedar
Scientific name: Calocedrus decurrens
Family: Cupressaceae
Life form: evergreen_tree
Native range: Sierra Nevada, Klamath Mountains, Cascade Range
Elevation: 600-2300 meters
Drought tolerance: moderate_to_high
Fire adaptation: thick_bark_moderate
Post-fire response: seed_regeneration
Priority for planting: 2
Planting density: [100, 200] stems/hectare
Survival rate: 55%
Nursery availability: moderate
Notes: Important component of mixed conifer forest. Distinctive aromatic foliage. Provides year-round cover for wildlife.

Species: Canyon Live Oak
Scientific name: Quercus chrysolepis
Family: Fagaceae
Life form: evergreen_tree
Native range: Throughout California mountains
Elevation: 100-2700 meters
Drought tolerance: very_high
Fire adaptation: vigorous_resprouter
Post-fire response: basal_and_root_sprouting
Priority for planting: 2
Planting density: [50, 150] stems/hectare
Survival rate: 70%
Nursery availability: moderate
Notes: Extremely adaptable species. Often does not need replanting due to vigorous resprouting. Important on rocky, steep terrain.

Species: Greenleaf Manzanita
Scientific name: Arctostaphylos patula
Family: Ericaceae
Life form: evergreen_shrub
Native range: Sierra Nevada, Klamath Mountains, Cascade Range
Elevation: 600-3000 meters
Drought tolerance: high
Fire adaptation: obligate_seeder
Post-fire response: seed_germination
Priority for planting: 3
Planting density: [100, 300] stems/hectare
Survival rate: 0%
Nursery availability: moderate
Notes: Early successional species after fire. Fixes nitrogen. Important pollinator resource. May compete with conifer regeneration if too dense.

Species: Douglas-fir
Scientific name: Pseudotsuga menziesii
Family: Pinaceae
Life form: evergreen_tree
Native range: Coast Ranges, Klamath Mountains, northern Sierra Nevada (scattered)
Elevation: 0-1800 meters
Drought tolerance: moderate
Fire adaptation: thick_bark_when_mature
Post-fire response: seed_regeneration
Priority for planting: 1
Planting density: [300, 600] stems/hectare
Survival rate: 75%
Nursery availability: high
Notes: Dominant species in Coast Range forests. Fast-growing, excellent for timber and carbon sequestration. Important for northern spotted owl habitat.

Species: Tanoak
Scientific name: Notholithocarpus densiflorus
Family: Fagaceae
Life form: evergreen_tree
Native range: Coast Ranges, Klamath Mountains
Elevation: 0-1500 meters
Drought tolerance: low_to_moderate
Fire adaptation: vigorous_resprouter
Post-fire response: basal_sprouting
Priority for planting: 2
Planting density: [100, 300] stems/hectare
Survival rate: 60%
Nursery availability: low_to_moderate
Notes: Important mast species for wildlife. Vigorous resprouter typically does not need replanting. Check for Sudden Oak Death presence before restoration planning.

Species: Coast Live Oak
Scientific name: Quercus agrifolia
Family: Fagaceae
Life form: evergreen_tree
Native range: Coast Ranges, Southern California
Elevation: 0-1200 meters
Drought tolerance: high
Fire adaptation: resprouter
Post-fire response: basal_sprouting
Priority for planting: 1
Planting density: [50, 150] stems/hectare
Survival rate: 65%
Nursery availability: high
Notes: Iconic California oak. Important for wildlife habitat. Drought and fire adapted. Cultural significance.

Species: Chamise
Scientific name: Adenostoma fasciculatum
Family: Rosaceae
Life form: evergreen_shrub
Native range: Throughout California chaparral
Elevation: 0-1800 meters
Drought tolerance: very_high
Fire adaptation: facultative_seeder_sprouter
Post-fire response: both_sprouting_and_seeding
Priority for planting: 2
Planting density: [500, 1500] stems/hectare
Survival rate: 70%
Nursery availability: moderate
Notes: Dominant chaparral species. Fire-adapted with both sprouting and seeding strategies. Important for erosion control immediately after fire.

Species: Toyon
Scientific name: Heteromeles arbutifolia
Family: Rosaceae
Life form: evergreen_shrub_small_tree
Native range: Throughout California
Elevation: 0-1200 meters
Drought tolerance: high
Fire adaptation: resprouter
Post-fire response: basal_sprouting
Priority for planting: 2
Planting density: [100, 300] stems/hectare
Survival rate: 75%
Nursery availability: high
Notes: California's Christmas berry. Excellent wildlife value. Attractive landscape plant. Highly recommended for restoration.

Species: Blue Oak
Scientific name: Quercus douglasii
Family: Fagaceae
Life form: deciduous_tree
Native range: Sierra Nevada foothills, Coast Range foothills, Central Valley edges
Elevation: 50-1200 meters
Drought tolerance: very_high
Fire adaptation: resprouter
Post-fire response: basal_sprouting
Priority for planting: 1
Planting density: [50, 150] stems/hectare
Survival rate: 55%
Nursery availability: moderate
Notes: Iconic foothill species. Extremely drought tolerant. Slow-growing but long-lived. Important for foothill savanna restoration.

Species: Deerbrush
Scientific name: Ceanothus integerrimus
Family: Rhamnaceae
Life form: deciduous_shrub
Native range: Sierra Nevada, Coast Ranges, Klamath Mountains
Elevation: 300-2100 meters
Drought tolerance: moderate
Fire adaptation: obligate_seeder
Post-fire response: seed_germination
Priority for planting: 2
Planting density: [200, 500] stems/hectare
Survival rate: 0%
Nursery availability: moderate
Notes: Important nitrogen-fixing pioneer species. Provides browse for deer. White flowers attract pollinators. Short-lived (10-20 years) but critical for early succession.

Species: Red Fir
Scientific name: Abies magnifica
Family: Pinaceae
Life form: evergreen_tree
Native range: Sierra Nevada, Klamath Mountains (high elevation)
Elevation: 1800-2800 meters
Drought tolerance: low
Fire adaptation: thin_bark
Post-fire response: seed_regeneration
Priority for planting: 2
Planting density: [200, 400] stems/hectare
Survival rate: 50%
Nursery availability: low
Notes: High-elevation species with long recovery times. Climate change may shift suitable habitat upward. Consider assisted migration planning.

Species: Gray Pine
Scientific name: Pinus sabiniana
Family: Pinaceae
Life form: evergreen_tree
Native range: Sierra Nevada foothills, Coast Range foothills
Elevation: 100-1200 meters
Drought tolerance: very_high
Fire adaptation: thin_bark_vulnerable
Post-fire response: seed_regeneration
Priority for planting: 2
Planting density: [50, 150] stems/hectare
Survival rate: 55%
Nursery availability: moderate
Notes: Distinctive open-crowned pine of hot, dry foothills. Large edible seeds important for wildlife and historically for Native Americans.

INVASIVE SPECIES WARNING: Yellow Star-thistle (Centaurea solstitialis). Threat level: high. Post-fire risk: very_high. Regions affected: sierra_foothills, coast_ranges, chaparral. Management: Early detection and rapid response critical. Mowing before seed set. Targeted herbicide.

INVASIVE SPECIES WARNING: Cheatgrass (Bromus tectorum). Threat level: high. Post-fire risk: very_high. Regions affected: sierra_nevada, modoc_plateau. Management: Creates grass-fire cycle. Priority control in first 2 years post-fire.

INVASIVE SPECIES WARNING: Scotch Broom (Cytisus scoparius). Threat level: high. Post-fire risk: high. Regions affected: coast_ranges, sierra_nevada. Management: Fire-stimulated germination. Pull or cut before seed set. Persistent seed bank.

INVASIVE SPECIES WARNING: French Broom (Genista monspessulana). Threat level: high. Post-fire risk: high. Regions affected: coast_ranges, bay_area. Management: Similar to Scotch Broom. Fire-adapted invasive.

INVASIVE SPECIES WARNING: Black Mustard (Brassica nigra). Threat level: moderate. Post-fire risk: high. Regions affected: southern_california, chaparral. Management: Can cause type conversion from shrubland to annual grassland.

CONFIDENCE LEVEL: Confidence Above 80
Evidence strength: Strong, multiple corroborating sources
Quantification: Required with confidence bounds
Permitted phrasing: The data shows..., Analysis indicates..., The site demonstrates..., Evidence confirms...

CONFIDENCE LEVEL: Confidence 60 To 80
Evidence strength: Moderate, consistent with interpretation
Quantification: Include uncertainty range
Permitted phrasing: The data suggests..., Analysis indicates likely..., The site appears to..., Evidence supports...

CONFIDENCE LEVEL: Confidence 40 To 60
Evidence strength: Limited, requires qualification
Quantification: Wide ranges or qualitative only
Permitted phrasing: Preliminary analysis suggests..., There may be..., It is possible that..., Limited data indicates...

CONFIDENCE LEVEL: Confidence Below 40
Evidence strength: Insufficient for claims
Quantification: Do not quantify - state data gap
Permitted phrasing: Insufficient data to assess..., Cannot be determined from available information..., Further investigation required..., Site-specific assessment needed...

CONFIDENCE LEVEL: No Data
Evidence strength: Data absent
Quantification: 
Permitted phrasing: Data not available for this parameter, Regional information not in knowledge base, Assessment not possible without field data
Prohibited phrasing: It is likely..., One would expect..., Typically in such cases..., Based on similar areas...

PROFESSIONAL RESTRAINT RULES
PROHIBITED STATEMENTS:
 - speculation_without_evidence: Creates liability and panic without basis
 - false_precision: Implies certainty that doesn't exist
 - generic_hazard_lists: Not site-specific, adds no value
 - emotional_alarmism: Unprofessional; fire is often beneficial
 - unqualified_recommendations: Requires site-specific assessment

GLOBAL BIOME: Tropical Rainforest
Climate: humid tropical
Fire Ecology: NOT_FIRE_ADAPTED
Natural Role of Fire: None - fire indicates degradation
Typical Regions: Amazon Basin, Congo Basin, Southeast Asian islands, Papua New Guinea, Central America
Post-fire Assessment:
 - Recovery: Slow to never - may convert to degraded state
 - Urgency: HIGH - fire is damaging event

GLOBAL BIOME: Tropical Savanna
Climate: wet-dry tropical
Fire Ecology: FIRE_DEPENDENT
Natural Role of Fire: Essential for maintaining grass-tree balance
Typical Regions: African savannas, Brazilian cerrado, Indian dry forest, Australian tropical woodland
Post-fire Assessment:
 - Recovery: Fast - grasses within weeks, trees slower
 - Urgency: LOW - fire is natural

GLOBAL BIOME: Mediterranean Shrubland
Climate: mediterranean (winter wet, summer dry)
Fire Ecology: FIRE_ADAPTED
Natural Role of Fire: Triggers regeneration, maintains shrub dominance
Typical Regions: California chaparral, Mediterranean maquis, Chilean matorral, South African fynbos, SW Australian kwongan
Post-fire Assessment:
 - Recovery: Good - 5-15 years to mature shrubland
 - Urgency: LOW unless invasive species threat

GLOBAL BIOME: Temperate Forest
Climate: temperate with distinct seasons
Fire Ecology: VARIABLE
Natural Role of Fire: Depends on forest type - some need fire, some don't
Typical Regions: Eastern North America, Western Europe, Eastern China, Southern Chile, New Zealand, Tasmania
Post-fire Assessment:
 - Recovery: Moderate - depends on severity
 - Urgency: MODERATE

GLOBAL BIOME: Temperate Conifer Forest
Climate: temperate with cold winters
Fire Ecology: HISTORICALLY_FIRE_MAINTAINED
Natural Role of Fire: Historically frequent low-severity fire maintained structure
Typical Regions: Western North America (Sierra Nevada, Cascades, Rockies), Pacific Northwest, Northern Europe (Scots pine), Siberia (southern), Japan mountains
Post-fire Assessment:
 - Recovery: SLOW - decades for canopy closure
 - Urgency: Depends on severity and seed source

GLOBAL BIOME: Boreal Forest
Climate: cold continental
Fire Ecology: FIRE_ADAPTED_STAND_REPLACEMENT
Natural Role of Fire: Infrequent crown fires drive mosaic pattern
Typical Regions: Canada boreal, Alaska interior, Russia taiga, Scandinavia, Northern Japan
Post-fire Assessment:
 - Recovery: Slow but natural - 50-200 years full recovery
 - Urgency: LOW - stand replacement is natural

GLOBAL BIOME: Eucalyptus Forest
Climate: temperate to subtropical Australian
Fire Ecology: EXTREMELY_FIRE_ADAPTED
Natural Role of Fire: Eucalypts evolved with intense fire; shapes ecosystem structure
Typical Regions: Eastern Australia, Western Australia, Tasmania, Naturalized: Portugal, California, Chile, South Africa
Post-fire Assessment:
 - Recovery: Excellent for eucalypts - epicormic sprouting within months
 - Urgency: LOW for eucalypts, MODERATE for understory

GLOBAL BIOME: Grassland Steppe
Climate: semi-arid to subhumid continental
Fire Ecology: FIRE_DEPENDENT
Natural Role of Fire: Frequent fire maintains grass dominance, prevents trees
Typical Regions: North American prairie, Eurasian steppe, South American pampas, African grasslands, Australian grasslands
Post-fire Assessment:
 - Recovery: Very fast - weeks to months
 - Urgency: VERY LOW - fire is beneficial

GLOBAL BIOME: Desert Scrubland
Climate: arid to semi-arid
Fire Ecology: NOT_HISTORICALLY_FIRE_PRONE
Natural Role of Fire: Historically rare due to sparse fuel
Typical Regions: Mojave Desert, Sonoran Desert, Sahara, Australian outback, Atacama
Post-fire Assessment:
 - Recovery: Very slow - decades to centuries
 - Urgency: HIGH if fire occurs - not natural

GLOBAL BIOME: Wetland Riparian
Climate: variable - defined by hydrology
Fire Ecology: FIRE_BUFFERED
Natural Role of Fire: Generally protected by water; upland fires may intrude
Typical Regions: River corridors worldwide, Floodplains, Marshes, Deltas
Post-fire Assessment:
 - Recovery: Fast if hydrology intact
 - Urgency: LOW if water regime preserved

ECOLOGICAL PRINCIPLE: Succession & Recovery
Description: Understanding natural ecosystem recovery patterns and when to intervene
Key concepts:
  - Natural regeneration vs active planting decisions
  - Pioneer species establish first, facilitating climax community
  - Fire-adapted species follow predictable succession patterns
  - Seed bank persistence varies by species and disturbance severity
Decision rules:
  - If burn severity < 50% AND seed source within 100m → natural regeneration likely
  - If burn severity > 70% AND no seed source within 500m → active planting required
  - Pioneer shrubs (Ceanothus, manzanita) establish within 1-3 years post-fire
  - Conifer regeneration may take 5-20 years to establish
California-specific:
  - Coast redwood resprouts from base even after severe fire
  - Chaparral species have fire-stimulated seed germination
  - Mixed conifer forests historically had 10-25 year fire return intervals
  - High-severity fire patches should be limited to <15% of landscape
Recovery timeframes:
  - Grassland: 5-10 years
  - Shrubland: 10-20 years
  - Mixed Forest: 20-50 years
  - Old Growth Forest: 100-300 years

ECOLOGICAL PRINCIPLE: Connectivity & Corridors
Description: Maintaining landscape connectivity for species movement and gene flow
Key concepts:
  - Fragmented habitats need linkages for population viability
  - Wildlife corridors enable species movement and migration
  - Gene flow prevents inbreeding depression
  - Connectivity increases resilience to climate change
Decision rules:
  - Prioritize restoration sites that connect existing habitat patches
  - Riparian corridors provide multi-species connectivity
  - Minimum corridor width: 100m for small mammals, 500m+ for large carnivores
  - Stepping stone habitats can supplement continuous corridors
California-specific:
  - Sierra Nevada to Coast Range connections critical for wide-ranging species
  - Highway underpasses and overpasses for wildlife crossing
  - Salmon need connected stream networks (dam removal, fish passage)
  - Mountain lion habitat connectivity increasingly fragmented

ECOLOGICAL PRINCIPLE: Hydrology & Wetlands
Description: Water flow restoration as foundation for ecosystem recovery
Key concepts:
  - Wetland restoration requires water flow restoration first
  - Floodplains provide critical ecosystem services
  - Riparian buffers protect water quality
  - Post-fire debris flows alter stream channels
Decision rules:
  - Restore hydrology BEFORE planting wetland vegetation
  - Maintain minimum 30m riparian buffer from streams
  - Reduce sediment loading post-fire through erosion control
  - Allow natural flood regimes where possible
California-specific:
  - California has lost >90% of historic wetlands
  - Vernal pools are globally rare and host endemic species
  - Atmospheric rivers cause high-intensity flooding
  - Drought cycles require drought-tolerant riparian species

ECOLOGICAL PRINCIPLE: Soil & Nutrients
Description: Soil health as foundation for restoration success
Key concepts:
  - Degraded soil limits restoration success
  - Legumes fix atmospheric nitrogen
  - Mycorrhizal networks essential for forest recovery
  - Soil organic matter takes decades to rebuild
Decision rules:
  - Test soil before restoration to identify limitations
  - Include nitrogen-fixing species (Ceanothus, lupine) in early plantings
  - Inoculate with native mycorrhizae when replanting conifers
  - Avoid soil compaction during restoration activities
California-specific:
  - Serpentine soils require specialized native species
  - Sierra Nevada soils often nitrogen-limited
  - Fire volatilizes nitrogen but ash provides other nutrients
  - Ceanothus species are important nitrogen-fixers post-fire

ECOLOGICAL PRINCIPLE: Keystone Species & Trophic Cascades
Description: Key species that disproportionately influence ecosystem function
Key concepts:
  - Removing invasive predators allows native prey recovery
  - Reintroducing native pollinators enhances reproduction
  - Beavers are ecosystem engineers that create wetlands
  - Oak trees are keystone mast providers for wildlife
Decision rules:
  - Identify and protect keystone species in restoration planning
  - Remove invasive species before planting natives
  - Plant species that support native pollinators
  - Consider trophic interactions, not just individual species

ECOLOGICAL PRINCIPLE: Climate Adaptation
Description: Planning restoration for future climate conditions
Key concepts:
  - Choose species suited to future climate, not just current
  - Assisted migration for climate refugees
  - Build resilience to drought, fire, and floods
  - Genetic diversity for adaptive capacity
Decision rules:
  - Use climate projections (2050, 2100) when selecting species
  - Source seeds from slightly warmer/drier populations
  - Favor drought-tolerant genotypes within native species
  - Maintain genetic diversity in planting stock

ECOLOGICAL PRINCIPLE: Community & Cultural Ecology
Description: Integrating human communities and traditional knowledge
Key concepts:
  - Traditional ecological knowledge (TEK) is valuable
  - Indigenous stewardship practices often fire-based
  - Local livelihoods depend on ecosystem services
  - Community engagement improves restoration success
Decision rules:
  - Consult with local tribes on restoration plans
  - Incorporate traditional burning practices where appropriate
  - Plan for sustainable harvest of restoration products
  - Engage local community in monitoring and stewardship

DECISION FRAMEWORK: Active Vs Passive Restoration
Description: When to actively plant vs allow natural recovery
Conditions favoring PASSIVE restoration (natural recovery):
  - Burn severity < 50%
  - Seed source within 100-200m
  - Native species seed bank likely intact
  - Resprouting species present
  - Low invasive species pressure
Conditions requiring ACTIVE restoration (planting):
  - Burn severity > 70%
  - No seed source within 500m
  - Type conversion risk high
  - High invasive species pressure
  - High erosion risk requiring rapid cover

DECISION FRAMEWORK: Prioritization Criteria
Description: How to prioritize restoration sites with limited resources
Ecological prioritization criteria:
  - Connectivity value (links habitat patches)
  - Biodiversity value (rare species, high diversity)
  - Ecosystem service value (water, carbon, recreation)
  - Restoration feasibility (soil, hydrology, access)
Social prioritization criteria:
  - Community support and engagement
  - Economic benefits to local communities
  - Cultural and spiritual significance
  - Risk reduction for communities
